Nick Scholfield will ride Spring Heeled in the Crabbie's Grand National at Aintree, replacing his expected mount Sam Winner, which may not run due to uncertainty from trainer Paul Nicholls. Scholfield has experience in the Grand National, having finished third in 2013 on Teaforthree, and will travel to Ireland to sit on Spring Heeled at Jim Culloty's stable. Meanwhile, Robbie McNamara will ride Lord Windermere, also trained by Culloty, in the National, and David Pipe's Soll is likely to secure a spot at the bottom of the weights after Double Ross was confirmed as a non-runner.
Eight faculty members at Columbia University have come to the defense of Dr. Mehmet Oz, who has been criticized by 10 doctors for promoting "quack treatments" on his TV show. While the faculty members acknowledge that Oz's on-air methods are problematic and "sully the reputation of Columbia University," they argue that his stellar work as a doctor and professor at the university should not be overshadowed by his TV persona. The faculty members suggest that Oz should start his show with a disclaimer stating that his opinions may not be evidence-based, and that regulatory guidance is needed to address the tension between his roles as a doctor and media personality.
The Duchess of Cornwall has launched her own honey, produced by bees in her Wiltshire garden, with all proceeds going to charity. The honey, priced at £20 per jar, is part of a growing trend of gourmet honey sales, which have increased by 45% at Selfridges since last year. The article reviews several luxury honeys, including the Duchess's, and finds that while some are worth the high price tag, others may not be, with the Duchess's honey receiving a perfect 5/5 score.
Aubrey de Grey, a 51-year-old biomedical theorist, believes that with the right "therapies," humans can live up to 500, 1,000, or even 5,000 years, and has gained support from high-profile figures in Silicon Valley, including PayPal boss Peter Thiel and Google co-founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin. De Grey's radical thesis is that ageing can be halted and even reversed by treating the human body like a vintage car, replacing and repairing damaged body parts at a cellular level, and he believes that technologies being developed now will allow us to achieve virtual immortality. Despite criticism from many academics, de Grey is empowered by the support of his billionaire backers and believes that within two decades, technology will have advanced far enough to allow us to replace and repair faulty genes and rejuvenate our bodies.
Researchers at the University of Bath and Yale University have developed a new material that can efficiently generate hydrogen from water, reducing the reliance on fossil fuels. The breakthrough uses a molecular catalyst to split water in an electrolyser, creating clean and storable hydrogen fuel with minimal energy loss. This innovation could make hydrogen a more viable option for storing energy from renewable sources like solar and wind power, potentially leading to more sustainable fuels for applications such as cars and airplanes.
A study by Stanford University researchers found that a popular Fisher-Price magnet set, designed to teach children to read and spell, inadvertently influenced the color-letter associations of some synesthetes, people with a neurological condition where two or more senses are involuntarily joined. The study analyzed data from 6,588 registered synesthetes and found that at least 6% of them, and up to 15% of those born after the toy's introduction, learned their color-letter pairings from the magnet set. The findings suggest that external factors, such as cultural influences or popular toys, can influence the associations of people already predisposed to synesthesia, but do not cause the condition itself.
Hannah Overton, a 37-year-old mother, has been cleared of all charges related to the 2006 death of her adopted son, Andrew Burd, who died from salt poisoning. Overton's conviction was overturned last year due to ineffective counsel, and despite initial plans to retry her, Nueces County district attorney Mark Skurka has decided to drop the case after re-examining the evidence and re-interviewing key witnesses. Overton, who spent seven years in prison, has maintained her innocence throughout, with her family and supporters claiming that Andrew's death was accidental and likely caused by a medical condition called pica.
Mary Cartwright, a 91-year-old great-grandmother, revisited the Drakelow Shadow Factory in Kidderminster, Worcestershire, where she worked as a metal tester in the underground laboratory from 1943 to 1945. The factory, one of 26 "shadow" sites built to mass-produce aircraft engines and parts during World War II, employed over 700 people and was designed to continue production even if bombed. Cartwright, who was the only woman in her department, recalled her time at the factory as a "bustling hive of activity" and an experience she enjoyed, despite having no prior experience in the field.
UFC fighters Chad Mendes and Ricardo Lamas are set to face off in the main event of UFC Fight Night, with both men showing respect for each other in the lead-up to the fight. Mendes, who has lost to featherweight champion Jose Aldo twice, believes that Aldo will win his upcoming fight against Conor McGregor and is hoping to secure a third title shot with a convincing win over Lamas. Lamas, meanwhile, is focused on performing well and earning a title shot, acknowledging that Mendes is a tough opponent but expressing confidence in his own abilities.
A chemical plant in Zhangzhou, China, producing the carcinogenic chemical paraxylene (PX), experienced a blast at an oil storage facility due to an oil leak. The fire has been brought under control by over 600 firefighters, and five people were injured by broken glass and are receiving treatment. This incident is not the first for the plant, which was relocated from a densely populated area in 2007 due to pollution concerns and had another explosion in 2013.
The MGM Grand in Las Vegas is preparing to host the highly anticipated boxing match between Floyd Mayweather and Manny Pacquiao, with 100,000 people expected to attend the event. To ensure a smooth experience, the hotel is stockpiling half a million bottles of beer and taking extensive security measures, including restricting access to the arena and concourses to ticket-holders and those with reservations. The event is expected to generate over a billion dollars in revenue for the Las Vegas economy, with the MGM Grand's non-gaming revenue, including food, beverages, and merchandise, playing a significant role in this figure.
Samantha Cameron made her first solo appearance of the general election campaign, visiting a special school in Rochester and Strood, a constituency held by UKIP's Mark Reckless, who defected from the Conservatives last year. The visit is seen as a statement of intent from the Conservatives, who are eager to win back the seat, and Mrs. Cameron's appearance is expected to be the first of several more stridently political interventions. The Prime Minister, David Cameron, has made no secret of his desire to defeat Reckless, having previously launched a scathing attack on his betrayal, and is due to participate in a seven-way debate with other party leaders.
The shooting of unarmed black driver Walter Scott by North Charleston police officer Michael Slager has raised concerns about policing practices, with many in the community saying that complaints of police misconduct are often dismissed without investigation. Slager's personnel file showed little indication of a history of excessive force, but a 2013 complaint of excessive use of force was exonerated without a thorough investigation, leading some to wonder if Scott's death could have been prevented. The incident has sparked calls for an independent citizens review board to review complaints against police, as many believe that law enforcement agencies are too quick to give themselves the benefit of the doubt.
Liberal Democrat leader Nick Clegg has admitted that his party is fighting "tooth and nail" in fewer than a tenth of Westminster seats, with a highly targeted strategy focused on around 60 key constituencies. Despite Clegg's optimism, senior party sources have privately conceded that the party's current total of 57 MPs is likely to be slashed to "in the thirties" due to a catastrophic collapse in support. The party is hoping that a reduced number of MPs could still allow them to hold the balance of power and potentially form part of a coalition government after the election.
Former Queens Park Rangers manager Harry Redknapp has expressed his willingness to return to management, but only if the right opportunity arises, citing his love for the game and his current good health after knee surgery. Redknapp, 68, resigned from QPR in February due to knee problems, but has since received offers, including a lucrative one to work abroad, which he declined. He will return to the dugout for a charity match on May 31, and has also been praising the work of Eddie Howe at Bournemouth, his former club, which is on the verge of promotion to the Premier League.
Moose Toys, a global toy company, has a unique and creative office space in Melbourne that encourages innovation and collaboration among employees, featuring a cubby-house meeting room, basketball court, and toy testing rooms. The company prioritizes fun and employee well-being, with activities such as table tennis, pinball, and karaoke nights, and rewards its employees with perks like a gold crown and cape for the Employee of the Year. With a focus on creativity and employee satisfaction, Moose Toys has become a successful and award-winning company, with products like Shopkins and Mighty Beanz bringing joy to kids worldwide.
A high-speed passenger train derailed on the outskirts of Split, Croatia, on Friday, resulting in at least six fatalities and 45 injuries. The train was traveling from Zagreb, the Croatian capital, to Split when it left the tracks about 12 miles from its destination. Croatian police have launched an investigation into the cause of the crash, with officials urging against speculation about the incident.
SBS journalist Scott McIntyre was fired after posting tweets on Anzac Day that referred to the event as the "cultification of an imperialist invasion" and accused Australian soldiers of committing war crimes. Australian Financial Review journalist Geoff Winestock defended McIntyre, calling Anzacs "racist yobs" and sparking further controversy. McIntyre's termination was met with both support and criticism, with some arguing that his right to free speech was being compromised, while others felt that his comments were unacceptable, especially given his taxpayer-funded position.
Labour received £1.9 million in donations in the first week of the UK election campaign, with 84% coming from just three trade unions, including a £1 million cheque from Unite. In contrast, the Conservatives received £501,850, with about a quarter coming from donors with links to hedge funds, while Ukip received £35,416, although it later received a £1 million donation from Daily Express owner Richard Desmond. Critics have accused Labour of being overly reliant on union funding, with nearly £7 in every £10 donated to the party since Ed Miliband became leader coming from unions, amounting to over £40 million.
Joshua Sweet, 20, was given a three-year community order for breaking into a 24-year-old teacher's home and sexually assaulting her while she lay in bed. The victim was left traumatized and "petrified" by the ordeal, and a Victim Support charity worker criticized the sentence, saying that victims deserve justice and that offenders should receive a punishment that fits their crime. Sweet was also ordered to do 150 hours of unpaid work and register as a sex offender for five years, but was not given a prison sentence despite the severity of the crime.
Walter Scott, a 50-year-old father of four, was shot and killed by Officer Michael Slager in Charleston, South Carolina, after running from the police. The incident sparked widespread outrage, with many celebrities, including Michelle Williams, Janelle Monáe, and Questlove, taking to social media to express their grief and anger. Officer Slager was charged with murder after a video emerged showing him firing at Scott eight times as he ran away with his back turned, contradicting Slager's initial claim that he feared for his life.
Six gay men were killed in two separate incidents in Baghdad, Iraq, over a 10-day period, according to an Iraqi Interior Ministry official. The victims were disowned by their relatives and targeted by their tribe after a meeting was held to decide their fate. A popular gathering spot for gays in Sadr City was also set on fire, highlighting the violent persecution faced by the LGBTQ+ community in Iraq.
Vestiaire Collective is selling a rare, made-to-measure pink crocodile Hermes Birkin bag embellished with rubies for £140,000, making it potentially Britain's most expensive handbag. The bag is considered a valuable investment due to its exclusivity, high-quality materials, and impeccable French craftsmanship, with experts saying it will increase in value over time. The price tag is equivalent to the cost of an Aston Martin DB9 Volante, and the bag is part of a brand with a strong heritage and a loyal following among stylish women, including celebrities like Kim Kardashian and Victoria Beckham.
Ukrainian boxer Wladimir Klitschko expressed his shock and upset over the ongoing crisis in his homeland, where a conflict with Russia has resulted in over 5,000 deaths. Klitschko, who is set to defend his heavyweight title against American challenger Bryant Jennings, emphasized the need for Western help in resolving the conflict and allowing Ukraine to become a democratic country. The boxer, who has a strong connection to Ukrainian politics through his brother Vitali, hopes for a peaceful resolution and an end to violence, not just in Ukraine but around the world.
Bruce Jenner's children, including Kim Kardashian and his sons Burt, Brandon, and Brody, are reportedly hesitant about his upcoming eight-episode docu-series on E! that will chronicle his transition into a woman. They are worried that the show might "de-class" what he has accomplished and are urging him to slow down on revealing too much of his journey on reality TV. However, Bruce believes the docu-series will educate people and create empathy, and he is committed to sharing his story, despite his children's concerns.
Robert Downey Jr. walked out of an interview with Channel 4 news presenter Krishnan Guru-Murthy after being asked about his past struggles with addiction. This incident is not an isolated one, as several other celebrities, including Naomi Campbell, Robert Pattinson, Justin Bieber, Peter Andre, and Rihanna, have also cut short interviews when asked about their personal lives. These instances highlight the tension that can arise when celebrities are pushed to discuss sensitive topics during interviews.
ISIS fighters have taken control of 90% of the Yarmouk refugee camp in Damascus, Syria, leaving a trail of death and destruction in their wake, with over 200 people killed in just seven days. Refugees who have fled the camp have shared harrowing stories of the atrocities they witnessed, including the slaughter of innocent children and the beheading of civilians. The camp, which was once home to 160,000 Palestinian refugees and Syrians, has been under siege for over a year, and the recent ISIS assault has forced thousands of people to flee, with many seeking refuge in nearby regime-held areas.
Millwall secured a crucial 2-0 win over Wigan Athletic in a Championship relegation six-pointer, with Jimmy Abdou scoring his first goal in two years and Magaye Gueye adding a second in stoppage time. The match was marred by three red cards, including one for Wigan's Martyn Waghorn, who was sent off for a senseless kick at Dan Harding, and another for Wigan's Jason Pearce for a dreadful tackle on Aiden O'Brien. The win keeps Millwall's hopes of survival alive, closing the gap to safety to just four points, and piles pressure on Rotherham United ahead of their match against Fulham.
Britons who buy their lunches out spend an average of £1,840 a year, but could save up to £1,300 by preparing their lunches at home. Food website Food52 offers a range of simple and delicious lunch ideas, from cheese and crackers to steamed Chinese buns and Vietnamese banh mi sandwiches. The website's "Not Sad Desk Lunch" series provides detailed recipes and inspiration for making healthy, cost-effective, and tasty lunches that can be easily assembled in the office.
Natural World Safaris is offering a rare, seven-day trip to Russia's Durminskoye Reserve in Khabarovsk, where tourists can sleep in the natural habitat of the endangered Siberian tiger for £3,500. The trip allows guests to explore the reserve, set camera traps, and track tiger footprints with the guidance of Russian conservationist Alexander Batalov, who has spent 20 years protecting the species. Although sightings are not guaranteed due to the tigers' elusive nature, the trip provides a unique opportunity to contribute to conservation efforts and possibly catch a glimpse of one of the world's most endangered animals.
A 24-year-old Algerian IT student, Sid Ahmed Ghlam, was arrested in Paris after shooting himself in the leg, and was found to have an arsenal of weapons and plans to attack churches in the area. DNA evidence links Ghlam to the murder of 33-year-old Aurelie Chatelain, a mother and fitness instructor who was shot dead in her car in a Paris suburb earlier that day. French authorities claim that Ghlam was planning a terrorist attack and had been in contact with a man in Syria who asked him to target a church, and that his arrest foiled an imminent attack.
Researchers have sequenced the microbiomes of Yanomami people, an indigenous group living in a remote Amazon village in Venezuela, and found that they harbor the highest diversity of bacteria and genetic functions ever reported in a human group. The study suggests that Western diets and lifestyles have a significant impact on our microbiomes, and that studying the microbiomes of people in remote areas may hold the key to understanding microbes that have been lost through modern practices. The findings also revealed that bacteria isolated from Yanomami microbiomes carry genes that confer resistance to man-made antibiotics, even though they had never been exposed to antibiotics, and could potentially lead to the development of new medical treatments.
Protesters in South Africa, mainly young black individuals, have vandalized statues of colonial-era figures, including British monarchs Queen Victoria and King George V, as well as Scottish-South African missionary Andrew Murray and British mining magnate Cecil John Rhodes. The vandalism is part of a larger movement to remove symbols of the country's colonial past, with some protesters accusing historical figures like Mahatma Gandhi of racism during their time in South Africa. The opposition party, the Economic Freedom Fighters, has supported the vandalism, while the government has backed the removal of the Rhodes statue, but not the violent removal of other colonial symbols.
Lizzi Crawford, a 32-year-old mother of six from Stoke-on-Trent, was inspired to lose weight after a child on a bus mistook her for being pregnant due to her size. Weighing 20 stone at the time, Lizzi dropped over 7 stone by adopting a healthier lifestyle, including cooking nutritious meals and attending fitness classes, despite being diagnosed with cervical cancer in 2012. She credits the support of her gym community and her newfound love of fitness for helping her achieve her weight loss goal and improving her mental and physical well-being.
Nafir Afzal, the UK's most senior Muslim prosecutor, has warned that hundreds of British teenagers view ISIS as "pop idols" and are at risk of being radicalized, drawing a comparison to the way young people idolize celebrities like One Direction and Justin Bieber. Afzal believes that a community-led approach, using young Muslim role models to mentor those at risk, is needed to prevent radicalization, rather than the current "stale" strategy used by police and security services. He warns that unless a new approach is taken, the UK could face another major terrorist attack, similar to the 7/7 bombings, as there are many "ticking time bombs" still in the country.
Paul Downton has been fired as the managing director of the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) following England's poor performance at the World Cup. The decision was made by new ECB chief executive Tom Harrison and chairman-elect Colin Graves, and was unanimous among the 14 members of the governing body's management board. The ECB will now create a new role, director of England cricket, which will focus on delivering world-class performance, and former England captains Michael Vaughan and Andrew Strauss are potential candidates for the position.
England flanker James Haskell posted a photo of himself dressed as Iron Man on Instagram to coincide with the premiere of the Avengers movie. Haskell, who is also the captain of the London Wasps, shared the image with a message referencing the movie and his partnership with Under Armour UK. The rugby player has had a successful career, playing for several teams including the Wasps, Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders, and has earned 57 caps for the England squad.
Good Morning Britain has launched the #SelfieEsteem campaign, encouraging people to post unfiltered selfies to promote self-acceptance and challenge the pressure to look perfect on social media. The campaign, which has been supported by various celebrities including Susanna Reid, Piers Morgan, and Jamelia, aims to address low self-esteem and body confidence issues. According to a survey conducted by the show, nearly half of women and a third of men are unhappy with their appearance, with weight being the top thing they would like to change.
Imran Uddin, a 25-year-old bio-science student at the University of Birmingham, was jailed for four months after admitting to hacking into university computers to change his grades. Uddin used keyboard spying equipment to record staff passwords, allowing him to access their accounts and alter his marks, including increasing one grade from 57% to 73%. The judge sentenced Uddin to prison as a deterrent, stating that his actions could have undermined public confidence in the degree system.
Hillary Clinton and her husband Bill were spotted taking a stroll in a park in Chappaqua, New York, as they enjoyed some downtime before she resumes her presidential campaign in New Hampshire. Clinton's campaign vans, nicknamed the "Scooby" vans, were also given some maintenance at a local body shop, where they were hand-washed and inspected. Clinton is set to hold roundtable discussions at a family-owned business and a community college in New Hampshire as part of her two-day swing through the state.
Six Leeds United players, including Mirco Antenucci and Giuseppe Bellusci, withdrew from the squad on the eve of a match against Charlton, citing injuries, in the latest incident of chaos at Elland Road. Striker Steve Morison expressed surprise at the situation, describing the season as one where "every day something different has happened," while former captain Trevor Cherry branded the players' actions a "disgrace" and called for them to be sacked. The incident has added to the turmoil at the club, with manager Neil Redfearn's position under threat and club president Massimo Cellino set to return from a ban in a fortnight's time.
Green Party leader Natalie Bennett has distanced herself from her boyfriend Jim Jepps' past blog posts, which included defending "rape fantasies" and describing paedophiles as "complex human beings." Jepps, who met Bennett online five years ago, wrote the posts on his blog "The Daily Maybe" until 2011, and later quit the Green Party in 2012. The Green Party has also disavowed Jepps' views, stating that they do not endorse his opinions and do not want to be associated with them.
Heather Mack, a 19-year-old accused of murdering her socialite mother in Bali, has filed a petition to transfer around $500,000 from her trust fund to care for her four-month-old daughter, Stella. The funds are intended to cover urgent needs such as clothing and baby wipes for Stella, who was born in prison and has been living with Mack in a crowded cell. Mack and her boyfriend, Tommy Schaefer, are awaiting sentencing for the murder, with prosecutors seeking 15 years for Mack and 18 years for Schaefer, but sparing them the death penalty due to Mack's remorse and her newborn baby.
A video of the fatal shooting of Walter Scott by North Charleston police officer Michael Slager has raised questions about the accounts given by Slager and other responding officers, who claimed Scott was shot during a struggle for Slager's Taser and that they administered CPR to Scott. However, the video appears to show Slager shooting Scott in the back as he ran away, and then planting his Taser next to Scott's body, with no evidence of CPR being performed. The discrepancies between the video and the officers' accounts have sparked outrage and calls for further investigation, with many accusing the police of attempting to cover up the incident.
Manchester United's Wayne Rooney has praised teammate Marouane Fellaini, describing him as one of the best in world football at bringing the ball down and relieving pressure. Fellaini has experienced a resurgence in form under manager Louis van Gaal, who has utilized him as a second striker behind Rooney, and has been instrumental in recent wins over Manchester City and Liverpool. United is now in third place in the Premier League with six consecutive league wins and will face a tough test against top-of-the-league Chelsea this weekend.
The FA Cup semi-finals were held at Wembley Stadium, with Arsenal facing Reading and Liverpool taking on Aston Villa. Despite some initial criticism, the matches proved to be exciting and memorable, with Reading pushing Arsenal to a thrilling match and Liverpool's Steven Gerrard being the focus of attention in the second semi-final. The BBC and BT Sport provided engaging coverage, capturing the atmosphere and emotions of the games, including a heart-wrenching moment when Reading's Adam Federici was consoled by his manager after the match.
Reading FC, a SkyBet Championship side, is set to face Premier League giants Arsenal in the FA Cup semi-final at Wembley on Saturday, with the Royals seeking to make their first-ever FA Cup final appearance. Manager Steve Clarke has told his players to focus solely on the game and not get caught up in the occasion, emphasizing that progression is the only objective. Despite being heavy underdogs, with odds of 14/1 to win, Clarke is confident that his team can make history if they play the "perfect game" against an in-form Arsenal side.
A rural area in Indiana, specifically Scott and Jackson counties, is experiencing a significant HIV outbreak with 142 people testing positive, largely due to the sharing of needles among IV drug users. The outbreak has prompted a public health emergency declaration and the deployment of additional resources, including a temporary clinic and a needle exchange program, to combat the spread of the disease. Health leaders are warning that the outbreak serves as a reminder of the ongoing risk of infectious diseases, particularly in rural areas with limited health resources, and are emphasizing the importance of education and vigilance in preventing the spread of HIV and other diseases.
Jeremy Clarkson will not face prosecution for an altercation with Top Gear producer Oisin Tymon, as Tymon has declined to press charges and North Yorkshire Police have completed their investigation. The incident, which occurred at a hotel in Hawes, North Yorkshire, led to Clarkson's sacking from the BBC show, despite widespread public support and a petition calling for his reinstatement. Clarkson is set to appear in a series of Top Gear Live shows alongside co-presenters Richard Hammond and James May, although the future of the show and its hosts remains uncertain.
The US Navy has charged six guards with assaulting detainees at Camp Bucca in Iraq in May, following an investigation by the Army Criminal Investigation Division. The investigation found that two detainees suffered minor bruises and eight others were confined overnight in a cell sprayed with a riot control agent. The six guards will face courts-martial, which are expected to start within 30 days at Camp Bucca, while seven other cases have been resolved through nonjudicial punishment.
The sentencing phase of the Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokhar Tsarnaev's trial has begun, with the jury hearing emotional testimony from the families of the four victims and survivors of the 2013 attack. The prosecution is seeking the death penalty, and the testimony is intended to show the impact of Tsarnaev's actions on the victims and their loved ones. The jury has heard heartbreaking stories of the victims, including Krystle Campbell, Lingzi Lu, Martin Richard, and Sean Collier, and has seen graphic images of the injuries sustained by survivors, including Gillian Reny and Celeste Corcoran, who lost both legs in the bombing.
Eleven-year-old Charlie Patino, a talented midfielder from Luton Town's academy, is being courted by top Premier League clubs Arsenal, Chelsea, and Tottenham, with a transfer fee of £10,000 on the table. Charlie's parents, Julio and Katy, are taking their time to consider the offers, prioritizing what's best for their son's future as a professional footballer. The family has visited the training grounds of the three clubs and is being guided through the process by Luton Town, with Charlie's parents emphasizing that there are no guarantees of success despite the promising opportunities.
A Bangkok Airways plane crashed at Koh Samui airport in Thailand, killing the pilot and injuring 37 people. The ATR-72 turboprop, carrying 68 passengers and four crew members, skidded and crashed after landing due to volatile winds. Seven people were seriously injured, and rescue workers were working to free the trapped co-pilot from the wreckage.
Tottenham striker Emmanuel Adebayor has expressed his commitment to the club, stating he will fight for his place in the team despite limited appearances this season. Adebayor, who joined Spurs in 2011, has made just 16 appearances and scored twice, largely due to the rise of Harry Kane. The 31-year-old Togo international is determined to see out the remainder of his contract in north London, praising the Premier League as "the best in the world."
